ce:section.ce:para:
The Photoluminescence behaviour of CDs with varying particle sizes and distribution of surface energy traps in the carbon core are probed. Fluorescent CDs are not pure Carbon materials. The surface modification with different passivation agents make the CDs fluorescent. Here we have used EDA as the passivation agent. The fluorescence spectra of the samples (Fig. 5
                     ) show an excitation-independent emission peak at 450 nm due to the uniform distribution of size and surface chemistry [31]. The fluorescence spectra features small tails extending into the long wavelength region. As observed in Fig. 4 the fluorescence intensity reaches an optimum value for the concentration 0.003 g/15 ml after which fluorescence quenching is observed due to enhancement in the non radiative relaxation. This is evidenced in the thermal lens measurements where an increase in concentration leads to a decrease in thermal diffusivity. An increase in the concentration of Carbon dots leads to enhanced scattering of thermal waves. The excitation spectra of carbon dots (Fig. 6
                     a) excited with xenon lamp with wavelength ranging from 190 nm to 1100 nm, show a prominent peak at 375 nm.
